The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the loco of a prehistoric pond, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Batlló House, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar shape to a skeleton, the locals seized it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its appealing colours, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that resembles the smoothly curved scales and omnipresent lines, all of which is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The cover of the house plays with onyric lines, delicate colors and textures extracted from nature and fauna.
By giving more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm, and carefully thought order are observed.
At night, the whole façade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentia and the torsion of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
The wet wood copies the frames of the windows, the paddles, the curtains of the doors, the mirrors and the letters.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample neighborhood in the number 43 of the animated commercial street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the industrial rich Josep Batlló, initially insisted on breaking down the former building and starting at zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, consisting of several apartments, did not design it alone, Antoni Gaudí.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project, ornaments arose for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the façade.
In the façade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the start of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Milá House and Güell Park in Gaudí, where there are other parts of it.
Because of its organic form, the locals soon after its completion seized it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began calling it "the house of the boxes".
It is also said that, on top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique system in the house for the central heating era with ventilating respirators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to have your forty-five degree inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the construction rules of the time and was not influenced by them.
Still, the construction had been granted permission from the beginning, although clearly in it the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its conclusion, the town was so affected by the result that it was requested to be corrected.
For example, he was disturbed that the construction included columns even to the public steel.
The arrangements were never made, rather the contrary: only 15 days after the town's request, Joseph Batlló requested permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner itself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and in the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The lower plant was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white blues and blues covering the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with both colors brings the highest light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which otherwise absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits, they confirmed, or discovered, that it was a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the boar, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches EUR 16.50, although students, pensioners and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount exceeds significantly the price of entry of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
