More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
The fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially intended for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device currently has the approximate size of a lock box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to inform about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but about another way to reduce the possibility of a tragedy," says Petro Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are placed in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet met such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what "cajita" is for and how it is used in case of emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bočkova warns about the fact that if the child doesn't want to wear it, he'll just pull it off.
"Even younger children show great creativity when they deliberately lose certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"In the past, the parents relied enormously on the mobiles, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočkova says.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will practically always check if the child carries some kind of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is expanding, you will also search for them, as their sale will undoubtedly be carried out with great publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can serve as aid.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If damage occurs, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person concerned."
"The most expensive devices have an inclination meter integrated, so if the person just goes off and remains mobile, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," Čech says.
