A longer index finger that the angular indicates a lower risk of suffering from cancer
Men who have the longest index that the anal are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the testosterone level, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, in particular if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles indicates.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, at the same time, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the indian finger of the right hand shorter than the abbreviation.
They had the same odds of suffering from prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men with less than 60%, the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined during the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone affects the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knew the study, but that he did not feel that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer could "be fully demonstrated".
