For a long time it has been considered that there are six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus by arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what's more possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it has.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press wheel to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated a large Internet speculation on the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "is shown is that in other planetary environments, there might be organisms that use other elements to stimulate their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider essential for life may not be so fixed," commented Charles Cockell, the Cathedral of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is innovative because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by another in the basic biochemical and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not carried out by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Astrology Institute, which conducted the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, it may be difficult for agencies to differentiate them."
"However, the arsenic is quite different than that it does not work as well as the phosphorus, so it comes in and, by some means, calls the biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, to which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
Microbio grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that it can naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or in another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, pointed out that the idea of replacing arsenic with phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove that it works.
The arsenic was more common in the first eras of the Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life could have used it.
"Yes, it suggests that there might be other means of generating life, not only the way life was formed on Earth in ancient times," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
