A Global Plan to Renewal of Lighting
Yesterday, the United Nations has proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in hundreds of countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GEI) in a quantity that is practically equivalent to one third of the additional decrease that must be made to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is reflected in the whole of major concrete projects that the United Nations expects to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bombs, which still monopolies between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bombs or, even better, by electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED") bombs, much of the 1,800 million tonnes (Gt) of GI emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary automotive park.
In Copenhagen, last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, a further 5 Gt of that amount should be reduced to stabilise, before 2020, the increase in temperatures in two centigrades to avoid uncontrolled.
In the incandescent pumps, 95% of the energy is released in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact pumps, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED pumps, energy consumption is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact pumps last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED pumps, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bomb, which allows us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in hundreds of countries.
These new bombs can also work with restodies and emit very little heat.
Above all, they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations regarding fluo-compact pumps, since they contain mercury and should be removed as hazardous wastes, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not the fluo-compact pumps, but the thermal coal plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that melts with the incandescent pumps.
Only in the United States, these centers emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of this international programme to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billions of dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2,500 million.
