Climate: French hats in their financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly disengaged (start or early) financing promises made by the developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30,000 million between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to providing EUR 7,200 million in three years and EUR 1,260 million in France (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has placed on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press wheel, a large complementary event, the distribution of booklets...
Transparency was a valuable result and was truly appreciated: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2,200 million in 2010, which puts it in the right path towards meeting its commitment of EUR 7,200 million in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Currently, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference in 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years in terms of funding for start-up.
Other countries have chosen similar references with respect to the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds.
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that each euro lent is equivalent to a given euro.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is appropriate to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... As much, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan should be calculated for its commitments (i.e. the equivalent to a kind of interest).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making a 91.5% loan (EUR 389.8 million) and a 8.5% grant (EUR 36.1 million); consult the EU document to see it for itself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among other things, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union brings a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only gives 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In summary, in its financing for start-up, France commits double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
With only EUR 36.1 million spent, it is possible to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional" as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has been involved in arbitration) could have a double negative impact both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can just pay?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter of early financing is a short-term reduction in the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the vast machinery that is the CNUCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of calculation for the years 2011 and 2012, with a view to respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move forward discussions on gambling bets in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
